# Tailwind CSS and Styling Conventions

## Tailwind CSS Usage
- Use Tailwind CSS classes for all styling
- Implement dark mode support with `dark:` prefixes
- Use consistent color schemes: blue, green, purple, gray, red, yellow variants
- Follow responsive design patterns with Tailwind breakpoints
- Use proper spacing and typography scales

## Component Styling Patterns
Reference [src/components/Card/index.tsx](mdc:src/components/Card/index.tsx) for variant-based styling:

```typescript
const getVariantStyles = () => {
  switch (variant) {
    case "blue":
      return {
        bg: "bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-900/20",
        title: "text-blue-900 dark:text-blue-100",
        description: "text-blue-700 dark:text-blue-300",
        border: "border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-800",
      };
    // ... other variants
  }
};
```

## Dark Mode Support
Always include dark mode variants:
- Background: `bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900/20`
- Text: `text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100`
- Borders: `border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700`

## Interactive Elements
For clickable components, use:
```typescript
const interactiveClasses = clickable 
  ? "hover:shadow-md hover:scale-105 transition-all duration-200 cursor-pointer"
  : "";
```

## Responsive Design
Use Tailwind breakpoints consistently:
- `sm:` for small screens (640px+)
- `md:` for medium screens (768px+)
- `lg:` for large screens (1024px+)
- `xl:` for extra large screens (1280px+)

## Global Styles
Reference [src/styles/globals.css](mdc:src/styles/globals.css) for global styling patterns and custom CSS variables.

## Accessibility
- Maintain proper color contrast ratios
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Implement proper focus states
- Test with screen readers
